phy.html |title=Annotated Bibliography |publisher=easterncougar.org \u2013 Cougar Rewilding Foundation}}\n\n==External links==\n{{NIE Poster|year=1905|Puma}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Cougar1.ogg|November 6, 2008}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=94 |website=IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group |title=Cougar ''Puma concolor''}}\n* [http://northernbushcraft.com/animalTracks/cougar/notes.htm Cougar Tracks]: How to identify cougar tracks in the wild\n* {{cite web |url=http://animals.nationalgeographic.com/animals/mammals/mountain-lion/?rptregcta=reg_free_np&rptregcampaign=20130924_rw_membership_r3p_c1#close-modal |title=Puma sounds |website=National Geographic Society|date=September 10, 2010 }}\n* [http://santacruzpumas.org/ Santa Cruz Puma Project]\n* [http://www.eprn.homestead.com/ Eastern Puma Research Network]\n* [http://felidaefund.org/ Felidae Conservation Fund]\n* [http://www.easterncougar.org/ Cougar Rewilding Foundation, formerly \"Eastern Cougar Foundation\"]\n* [http://www.cougarnet.org/ The Cougar Network --Using Science to Understand Cougar Ecology]\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.mountainlion.org/about_the_foundation.asp |website=Mountain Lion Foundation |title=Saving America's Lion}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040831044323/http://www.savethecougar.org/ SaveTheCougar.org]: Sightings of cougars in Michigan\n* [http://www.cougarfund.org/ The Cougar Fund \u2013 Protecting America's Greatest Cat.] A Definitive Resource About Cougars] Comprehensive, non-profit [[501(c)(3)]] site with extensive information about cougars, from how to live safely in cougar country, to science abstracts, hunting regulations, state-by-state cougar management/policy info, and rare photos and videos of wild cougars.\n* [http://sagehen.ucnrs.org/Documents/visitors/wildlife/lion.pdf Living with California Mountain Lions]\n* [https://www.statesmanjournal.com/story/news/2018/09/11/oregons-first-ever-fatal-cougar-attack-reported-near-mount-hood/1272976002/ Oregon's first fatal cougar attack in the wild claims hiker near Mount Hood]\n\n{{Carnivora|Fe.}}\n{{North American Game}}\n\n{{Featured article}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q35255}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Puma (genus)]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1771]]\n[[Category:Man-eating species]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus]]\n[[Category:Felids of Central America]]\n[[Category:Felids of North America]]\n[[Category:Felids of South America]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the California chaparral and woodlands]]\n[[Category:Apex predators]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene carnivorans]]\n[[Category:Quaternary carnivorans]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene mammals of North America]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene mammals of South America]]\n[[Category:Extant Middle Pleistocene first appearances]]\n", "name_user": "McGehee", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCharacteristics:On a page with multiple pictures of mature cougars, somebody captioned this photo with the claim that adult cougars have blue eyes. Corrected.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cougar"}
{"title_page": "Ruby Neri", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name = Ruby Rose Neri\n| other_names = Reminisce, REM\n| birth_date = 1970\n| birth_place      = \n| education = [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (MFA, 1998), [[San Francisco Art Institute]] (BFA, 1994){{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n| known_for = [[Painting]], [[sculpture]], [[ceramics]], [[graffiti]], [[murals]]\n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| movement      = [[Mission School]]\n}}\n'''Ruby Rose Neri''' is an artist based in [[Los Angeles]], California. She was born and raised in California's Bay Area, drawing creative influence from her parents and their friends.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Berzon|first=Stephanie|date=2014|title=Hands on Materials: An Interview with Ruby Neri|url=|journal=ArtSlant|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Her father is [[Manuel Neri]], a prolific sculptor associated with the [[Bay Area Figurative Movement]], and her mother, Susan Neri, is a graphic designer.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dame|first=The Dinghy|date=2013|title=Meet Susan Neri of South Forty|url=|journal=Floating Homes|volume=06|pages=3\u20134|via=}}</ref> Neri is both a painter and a sculptor, and has worked with a wide array of materials including clay, plaster, bronze, steel, fiberglass, glaze, acrylic, oil, and spray paint.<sup>[8]</sup> Lately, Neri has focused her practice and is primarily making clay sculpture.<sup>[7]</sup> Her work is based in abstraction and figuration, drawing inspiration from Bay Area Figuration, [[German Expressionism]], [[graffiti]], and [[folk art]]. Neri uses horses as a common motif in her work, which serves as a personal symbol of her youth.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''Reminisce''' (aka '''REM''', pseudonyms of '''Ruby Rose Neri''')<ref name=remremembered>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160303220630/http://people.tribe.net/amor/blog/6eca1dd4-ac79-4566-a4ed-824d2e7d195f \"Reminisce Remembered\"] by Amor Sans Blague, ''Motility Blog'', April 30, 2005.</ref>  is a [[sculptor]], [[Painting|painter]], and former [[street art]]ist from [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]] and [[Los Angeles]], California, known for her portrayal of [[horse]]s.\n\n== Early life and influences ==\nBorn to a family of artists, Neri was exposed to ways of making and expressing from a very young age. Her mother's ability to render realistic images of human figures and horses proved to have a heavy  influence in Neri's early work as a painter and a graffiti artist in the 1990s, and as subjects still remain in her work today.\n\nThe style that her father developed as a sculptor during the second generation of Bay Area Figuration also influenced Neri's work, which emerged later in her life as she made the switch from painting to sculpture.<ref name=\":0\" /> Comparing one of Neri's earlier figurative sculptures to the work that her father is best known for, a number of visual similarities are apparent and evoke the closeness of their relationship. Though their handling of materials, surface treatment, and subject are akin at first glance, a deeper look might reveal subtle yet important differences.\n\n== Undergraduate studies: San Francisco Art Institute & The Mission School ==\nIn 1992, Ruby moved from [[Nicasio, California]] to [[San Francisco]], CA to study painting at the [[San Francisco Art Institute]]. Ruby's father, Manuel was teaching at SFAI while Ruby was a student, making his presence and influence in her education almost unavoidable.<ref name=\":0\" /> Ruby stated in an interview that, \u201cDuring undergrad at SFAI all my teachers were either my father\u2019s students or his contemporaries; I felt very limited by this but was unaware of it at the time\u201d.<ref name=\":0\" /> Despite this limitation, her experience at SFAI proved to be one of the most influential times in her life and career.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Energy That is All Around|last=Boas|first=Natasha|publisher=San Francisco Art Institute and Grey Art Gallery|year=2014|isbn=|location=San Francisco|pages=}}</ref>\n\nWhile there, she became close friends with artists [[Alicia McCarthy]], [[Barry McGee]], and Margaret Kilgallen.<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup> She and her friends would later become associated with the movement known as \u201c[[Mission School|The Mission School]]\u201d, canonized by the [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]] in 2010, when the institution deemed the Mission School, \u201c...the most significant art movement to emerge out of San Francisco in the late twentieth century\u201d.<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup> In the book \u201cEnergy That is All Around\u201d, Curator Hesse McGraw credits this group of deeply connected artists with changing the \u201clanguage\u201d of SFAI as an institution, stating that, \u201cThey have come to reflect the highest achievement of an art school, which is to cultivate artists whose work adds new strains to contemporary art, and perhaps more importantly, who care about each other enough to add life to a community of artists\u201d.<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup>\n\nMembers of The Mission School were working within a special combination of time and place, growing up in and around art school during the early to mid-1990s during the pre-internet age, when San Francisco still possessed its \u201clegendary bohemian-inflected vibe\u201d.<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup> They were gearing up to start their art careers at the \u201cvery cusp of the digital age\u201d<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup>, and with San Francisco's proximity to Silicon Valley they would go on to, \u201cexperience a culture-shattering dot-com technology boom/bust in the mid to late \u201890s\u201d<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup>, which brought with it a rampant case of gentrification.<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup>\n\nThrough these shared experiences, The Mission School artists cultivated an anti-establishment, anti-consumerist outlook on the world. Their collective energy, worldview and active participation in various \u201cdisobedient\u201d subcultures lead to the shared aesthetic in their artworks, an aesthetic that is visibly connected to Neri's oeuvre.<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup>\n\nDuring Neri's time at SFAI, she formed her network of friends through a common interest in graffiti, which ultimately lead to her inclusion in the Mission School movement.<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup> Although writing graffiti was more of a social and sometimes political outlet than a serious artistic pursuit for Neri, the influence of her time spent painting in the street is still visible in her work today.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Graduate studies: UCLA ==\nIn 1994, Ruby moved from the Bay Area to Los Angeles, and would go on to earn her [[Master of Fine Arts|Master's of Fine Art]] from the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] in 1998. There, she made the gradual transition from producing mostly painting to sculpture. Her first foray into sculpture was through plaster, which she used to create abstracted figures of humans and horses in a style reminiscent of [[Cubism|cubist]] painting. This transition was perhaps sparked by the fact that she was, for the first time, free of the impositions of her father's legacy. Her frustration with the weight of painting's history encouraged this transition into sculpture to continue. As Neri states in an interview for the Los Angeles Review of Books, \u201cPainting is so demanding in terms of its history. The whole idea of what painting is became problematic for me and I didn\u2019t have the time to address all the issues that were not interesting to me at all...\u201d.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Holloway|first=Evan|date=2014|title=Artist Portfolio - Ruby Neri|url=|journal=Los Angeles Review of Books|volume=|pages=56\u201371|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Current work ==\nHaving exhibited since the mid-1990s, Neri maintains a stimulating artistic practice through a commitment to experimentation.<ref name=\":2\" /> Throughout her career, she has explored the possibilities in paint (oil, acrylic, spray), plaster, and clay - her current work is a visual culmination of those explorations. Neri deftly combines elements of figuration, abstraction, graffiti, and folk art through clay, plaster, and paint to create complex, expressive and kinetic sculptures.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nNeri's most recent accomplishment is her inclusion in the book, \u201cVitamin C: Clay and Ceramic in Contemporary Art\u201d, published in 2017.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Vitamin C: Clay and Ceramic in Contemporary Art|last=Lilley|first=Claire|publisher=Phaidon|year=2017|isbn=|location=New York City|pages=}}</ref> The book is a global survey of one hundred of today's leading clay and ceramic artists - Neri is included alongside notable artists such as Anders Ruhwald, [[Edmund de Waal]], [[Theaster Gates]], [[Ron Nagle]], [[Grayson Perry]], and [[Betty Woodman]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn an interview conducted for Phaidon, the publishers of \u201cVitamin C\u201d, she notes the various ceramic artists she was surrounded by and exposed to throughout her childhood, including [[Richard Shaw (artist)|Richard Shaw]], [[Viola Frey]], [[Peter Voulkos]], and [[Robert Arneson]], amongst others.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.phaidon.com/agenda/art/articles/2017/november/01/ruby-neri-why-i-create/|title=Ruby Neri - Why I Create|last=|first=|date=2017|website=Phaidon|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 26, 2017}}</ref> She also states that, \u201cAlthough I was primarily a painter for many years, ceramics has been a major influence on how I approach materials and how I physically manipulate objects\u201d.<ref name=\":4\" /> Despite and perhaps because of her lack of formal training in ceramics, Neri manipulates the material with a sense of naivety that demonstrates her belief that the history of ceramics is, like painting, \u201coppressive\u201d.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\nNeri states in the same interview that she is currently most excited by the work of Viola Frey, citing the scale of Frey's monumental pieces and her fearlessness as a woman working amongst men as key inspirations.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neri, Ruby}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American graffiti artists]]\n[[Category:Modern sculptors]]\n[[Category:People from Marin County, California]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Art Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:UCLA School of the Arts and Architecture alumni]]\n[[Category:American women painters]]\n[[Category:Mission District, San Francisco]]\n[[Category:American women sculptors]]\n[[Category:Women graffiti artists]]\n[[Category:Women muralists]]\n[[Category:American ceramists]]\n[[Category:Artists from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:American artists of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from California]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century ceramists]]\n[[Category:American women ceramists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name = Ruby Rose Neri\n| other_names = Reminisce, REM\n| birth_date = 1970\n| birth_place      = \n| education = [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (MFA, 1998), [[San Francisco Art Institute]] (BFA, 1994){{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n| known_for = [[Painting]], [[sculpture]], [[ceramics]], [[graffiti]], [[murals]]\n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| movement      = [[Mission School]]\n}}\n'''Ruby Rose Neri''' is an artist based in [[Los Angeles]], California. She was born and raised in California's Bay Area, drawing creative influence from her parents and their friends.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Berzon|first=Stephanie|date=2014|title=Hands on Materials: An Interview with Ruby Neri|url=|journal=ArtSlant|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Her father is [[Manuel Neri]], a prolific sculptor associated with the [[Bay Area Figurative Movement]], and her mother, Susan Neri, is a graphic designer.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dame|first=The Dinghy|date=2013|title=Meet Susan Neri of South Forty|url=|journal=Floating Homes|volume=06|pages=3\u20134|via=}}</ref> Neri is both a painter and a sculptor, and has worked with a wide array of materials including clay, plaster, bronze, steel, fiberglass, glaze, acrylic, oil, and spray paint.<sup>[8]</sup> Lately, Neri has focused her practice and is primarily making clay sculpture.<sup>[7]</sup> Her work is based in abstraction and figuration, drawing inspiration from Bay Area Figuration, [[German Expressionism]], [[graffiti]], and [[folk art]]. Neri uses horses as a common motif in her work, which serves as a personal symbol of her youth.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''Reminisce''' (aka '''REM''', pseudonyms of '''Ruby Rose Neri''')<ref name=remremembered>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160303220630/http://people.tribe.net/amor/blog/6eca1dd4-ac79-4566-a4ed-824d2e7d195f \"Reminisce Remembered\"] by Amor Sans Blague, ''Motility Blog'', April 30, 2005.</ref>  is a [[sculptor]], [[Painting|painter]], and former [[street art]]ist from [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]] and [[Los Angeles]], California, known for her portrayal of [[horse]]s.\n\n== Early life and influences ==\nBorn to a family of artists, Neri was exposed to ways of making and expressing from a very young age. Her mother's ability to render realistic images of human figures and horses proved to have a heavy  influence in Neri's early work as a painter and a graffiti artist in the 1990s, and as subjects still remain in her work today.\n\nThe style that her father developed as a sculptor during the second generation of Bay Area Figuration also influenced Neri's work, which emerged later in her life as she made the switch from painting to sculpture.<ref name=\":0\" /> Comparing one of Neri's earlier figurative sculptures to the work that her father is best known for, a number of visual similarities are apparent and evoke the closeness of their relationship. Though their handling of materials, surface treatment, and subject are akin at first glance, a deeper look might reveal subtle yet important differences.\n\n== Undergraduate studies: San Francisco Art Institute & The Mission School ==\nIn 1992, Ruby moved from [[Nicasio, California]] to [[San Francisco]], CA to study painting at the [[San Francisco Art Institute]]. Ruby's father, Manuel was teaching at SFAI while Ruby was a student, making his presence and influence in her education almost unavoidable.<ref name=\":0\" /> Ruby stated in an interview that, \u201cDuring undergrad at SFAI all my teachers were either my father\u2019s students or his contemporaries; I felt very limited by this but was unaware of it at the time\u201d.<ref name=\":0\" /> Despite this limitation, her experience at SFAI proved to be one of the most influential times in her life and career.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Energy That is All Around|last=Boas|first=Natasha|publisher=San Francisco Art Institute and Grey Art Gallery|year=2014|isbn=|location=San Francisco|pages=}}</ref>\n\nWhile there, she became close friends with artists [[Alicia McCarthy]], [[Barry McGee]], and Margaret Kilgallen.<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup> She and her friends would later become associated with the movement known as \u201c[[Mission School|The Mission School]]\u201d, canonized by the [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]] in 2010, when the institution deemed the Mission School, \u201c...the most significant art movement to emerge out of San Francisco in the late twentieth century\u201d.<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup> In the book \u201cEnergy That is All Around\u201d, Curator Hesse McGraw credits this group of deeply connected artists with changing the \u201clanguage\u201d of SFAI as an institution, stating that, \u201cThey have come to reflect the highest achievement of an art school, which is to cultivate artists whose work adds new strains to contemporary art, and perhaps more importantly, who care about each other enough to add life to a community of artists\u201d.<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup>\n\nMembers of The Mission School were working within a special combination of time and place, growing up in and around art school during the early to mid-90's during the pre-internet age, when San Francisco still possessed its \u201clegendary bohemian-inflected vibe\u201d.<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup> They were gearing up to start their art careers at the \u201cvery cusp of the digital age\u201d<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup>, and with San Francisco's proximity to Silicon Valley they would go on to, \u201cexperience a culture-shattering dot-com technology boom/bust in the mid to late \u201890s\u201d<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup>, which brought with it a rampant case of gentrification.<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup>\n\nThrough these shared experiences, The Mission School artists cultivated an anti-establishment, anti-consumerist outlook on the world. Their collective energy, worldview and active participation in various \u201cdisobedient\u201d subcultures lead to the shared aesthetic in their artworks, an aesthetic that is visibly connected to Neri's oeuvre.<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup>\n\nDuring Neri's time at SFAI, she formed her network of friends through a common interest in graffiti, which ultimately lead to her inclusion in the Mission School movement.<sup><ref name=\":1\" /></sup> Although writing graffiti was more of a social and sometimes political outlet than a serious artistic pursuit for Neri, the influence of her time spent painting in the street is still visible in her work today.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Graduate studies: UCLA ==\nIn 1994, Ruby moved from the Bay Area to Los Angeles, and would go on to earn her [[Master of Fine Arts|Master's of Fine Art]] from the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] in 1998. There, she made the gradual transition from producing mostly painting to sculpture. Her first foray into sculpture was through plaster, which she used to create abstracted figures of humans and horses in a style reminiscent of [[Cubism|cubist]] painting. This transition was perhaps sparked by the fact that she was, for the first time, free of the impositions of her father's legacy. Her frustration with the weight of painting's history encouraged this transition into sculpture to continue. As Neri states in an interview for the Los Angeles Review of Books, \u201cPainting is so demanding in terms of its history. The whole idea of what painting is became problematic for me and I didn\u2019t have the time to address all the issues that were not interesting to me at all...\u201d.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Holloway|first=Evan|date=2014|title=Artist Portfolio - Ruby Neri|url=|journal=Los Angeles Review of Books|volume=|pages=56\u201371|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Current work ==\nHaving exhibited since the mid-1990s, Neri maintains a stimulating artistic practice through a commitment to experimentation.<ref name=\":2\" /> Throughout her career, she has explored the possibilities in paint (oil, acrylic, spray), plaster, and clay - her current work is a visual culmination of those explorations. Neri deftly combines elements of figuration, abstraction, graffiti, and folk art through clay, plaster, and paint to create complex, expressive and kinetic sculptures.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nNeri's most recent accomplishment is her inclusion in the book, \u201cVitamin C: Clay and Ceramic in Contemporary Art\u201d, published in 2017.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Vitamin C: Clay and Ceramic in Contemporary Art|last=Lilley|first=Claire|publisher=Phaidon|year=2017|isbn=|location=New York City|pages=}}</ref> The book is a global survey of one hundred of today's leading clay and ceramic artists - Neri is included alongside notable artists such as Anders Ruhwald, [[Edmund de Waal]], [[Theaster Gates]], [[Ron Nagle]], [[Grayson Perry]], and [[Betty Woodman]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn an interview conducted for Phaidon, the publishers of \u201cVitamin C\u201d, she notes the various ceramic artists she was surrounded by and exposed to throughout her childhood, including [[Richard Shaw (artist)|Richard Shaw]], [[Viola Frey]], [[Peter Voulkos]], and [[Robert Arneson]], amongst others.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.phaidon.com/agenda/art/articles/2017/november/01/ruby-neri-why-i-create/|title=Ruby Neri - Why I Create|last=|first=|date=2017|website=Phaidon|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 26, 2017}}</ref> She also states that, \u201cAlthough I was primarily a painter for many years, ceramics has been a major influence on how I approach materials and how I physically manipulate objects\u201d.<ref name=\":4\" /> Despite and perhaps because of her lack of formal training in ceramics, Neri manipulates the material with a sense of naivety that demonstrates her belief that the history of ceramics is, like painting, \u201coppressive\u201d.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\nNeri states in the same interview that she is currently most excited by the work of Viola Frey, citing the scale of Frey's monumental pieces and her fearlessness as a woman working amongst men as key inspirations.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neri, Ruby}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American graffiti artists]]\n[[Category:Modern sculptors]]\n[[Category:People from Marin County, California]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Art Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:UCLA School of the Arts and Architecture alumni]]\n[[Category:American women painters]]\n[[Category:Mission District, San Francisco]]\n[[Category:American women sculptors]]\n[[Category:Women graffiti artists]]\n[[Category:Women muralists]]\n[[Category:American ceramists]]\n[[Category:Artists from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:American artists of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from California]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century ceramists]]\n[[Category:American women ceramists]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruby_Neri"}
{"title_page": "G\u00f8sta Esping-Andersen", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = G\u00f8sta Esping-Andersen\n| image       =\n| image_size  =\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1947|11|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[N\u00e6stved]], [[Denmark]]\n|field = [[Sociology]], [[Social Policy|Comparative Social Policy]]\n|work_institutions = [[Harvard University]]<br />[[European University Institute]]<br />[[Pompeu Fabra University]]\n|alma_mater = [[University of Copenhagen]]<br />[[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]\n|thesis_title = Social Class, Social Democracy and State Policy: Parity Policy and Party Decomposition in Denmark and Sweden<ref>{{cite book |last=Esping-Andersen |first=G\u00f8sta |date=1978 |title=Social Class, Social Democracy and State Policy: Parity Policy and Party Decomposition in Denmark and Sweden |type=Ph.D. |chapter= |publisher=University of Wisconsin-Madison |docket= |oclc= 705977095 |id={{ProQuest|302910232}} }}</ref>\n|known_for = ''Welfare Regimes''{{*}}''Three Worlds of Welfare Capitalism''\n}}\n\n'''G\u00f8sta Esping-Andersen''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8j\u00f8st\u00e6 \u02c8espe\u031d\u014b \u02c8\u0251n\u0250sn\u0329|pron}}) (born 24 November 1947)<ref name=Congress>{{cite web |title= Esping-Andersen, G\u00f8sta, 1947\u2013 |url= http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n84135803.html |publisher= Library of Congress |accessdate= 4 January 2015 |quote= pub. info sheet (b. 11/24/47, Naestved, Denmark; Ph.D., 1978, Univ. of Wisconsin-Madison, sociology; Dept. of Sociology, Harvard Univ., assoc. prof., Cambrdige, Mass.) }}</ref> is a Danish [[sociologist]] whose primary focus has been on the [[welfare state]] and its place in [[capitalism|capitalist economies]]. [[Jacob Hacker]] describes him as the \"dean of welfare state scholars.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hacker|first=Jacob|title=Beyond continuity:institutional change in advanced political economies|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2005|isbn=|location=|pages=|chapter=Policy Drift: The Hidden Politics of US Welfare State Retrenchment}}</ref> Over the past decade his research has moved towards family demographic issues. A synthesis of his work was published as ''Families in the 21st Century'' (Stockholm, SNS, 2016). \n\nEsping-Andersen is [[professor emeritus]] at [[Pompeu Fabra University]] in [[Barcelona]] ([[Spain]]), and member of the Scientific Committee of the [[Juan March Institute]] and of the Board of Trustees and the Scientific Council at the [[IMDEA]] Social Sciences Institute, both in [[Madrid]] ([[Spain]]). He is a member of the American Academy of Social Sciences and the British Academy. He was awarded a honoris doctor causa from Copenhagen University in 2012. He is now research professor at Bocconi University in Milano.\n\n==Major works==\nHis major, most influential and highly cited book titled ''[[The Three Worlds of Welfare Capitalism]]''<ref>{{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = The three worlds of welfare capitalism | publisher = Princeton University Press | location = Princeton, New Jersey | year = 1990 | isbn = 9780069028573 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta |  ref = harv | doi = 10.1080/15579336.1990.11770001 | title = 4 the Three Political Economies of the Welfare State | journal = International Journal of Sociology | volume = 20 | issue = 3 | pages = 92\u2013123 | year = 1990 }}</ref> was published in 1990 and it laid out three main types of [[welfare state]]s, in which modern developed capitalist nations cluster: \n*Liberal\n*Corporatist-Statist\n*Social Democratic\n\nIt is important to note that these categories have little to do with the contemporary labels of [[American politics]], and rather have much more to do with general [[political theory]]. The traditional examples of the three types of welfare states are the [[United States]] (liberal), [[Germany]] (corporatist-statist) and [[Sweden]] (social democratic).\n\nOther sociologists and political scientists went on to apply his theoretical analysis to the real world. One such example is a book entitled ''[[Real Worlds of Welfare Capitalism]]'', written by [[Robert E. Goodin]], Bruce Headey, Ruud Muffels, and Henk-Jan Dirven.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Goodin | first1 = Robert E. | last2 = Headey | first2 = Bruce | last3 = Muffels | first3 = Rudd | last4 = Dirven | first4 = Henk-Jan | author-link1 = Robert E. Goodin | title = The real worlds of welfare capitalism | url = https://archive.org/details/realworldsofwelf00robe | url-access = registration | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge, U.K. New York | year = 1999 | isbn = 9780521596398 }}</ref> While some critics claim Esping-Andersen's categories are becoming outdated, many political scientists are attracted by its intuitive simplicity.\n\nIn the past decade, his research has moved to demographic issues and in particular to the consequences of women's changing roles. He has, most notably, developed a multiple equilibrium framework for the understanding of changing family behavior. See in particular his ''''Families in the 21st Century and Esping-Andersen and Billari (2015) 'Retheorizing family demographic change'. ''Population and Development Review (2015)''''''''\n\n==Criticism==\n\nThe evolving nature of welfare states often makes it difficult to categorize. Arguably, many welfare states have components from some or all typologies, making them more akin to points on a continuum rather than rigid typologies, a fact Esping-Andersen acknowledges in his writings.\n\nAccording to French sociologist, [[Georges Menahem]], Esping-Andersen's \"[[decommodification]] index\" aggregates both qualitative and quantitative variables for \u201dsets of dimensions\u201d which fluid, and pertain to three very different areas.  Similarly, Menahem has concerns regarding the validity of the index, and its potential for replication.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Menahem | first = Georges | author-link = Helena Flam | title = The decommodified security ratio: A tool for assessing European social protection systems | journal = [[International Social Security Review]] | volume = 60 | issue = 4 | pages = 69\u2013103 | doi = 10.1111/j.1468-246X.2007.00281.x | date = October 2007 | ref = harv | url = https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00198398/file/ISSR-2007-4-TheDSRatoolforassessing.pdf }}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n=== Books ===\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = Social class, social democracy and state policy: party policy and party decomposition in Denmark and Sweden | publisher = Institute of Organization and Industrial Sociology | location = Copenhagen | year = 1980 | isbn = 9788770341790 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Esping-Andersen | first1 = G\u00f8sta | last2 = Zeitlin | first2 = Maurice | last3 = Friedland | first3 = Roger | title = Political power and social theory: a research annual, volume 3 | publisher = Jai Press Inc. | location = Greenwich, Connecticut | year = 1982 | isbn = 9780892322046 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = Politics against markets: the social democratic road to power | publisher = Princeton University Press | location = Princeton, New Jersey | year = 1985 | isbn = 9780691028422 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/politicsagainstm0000espi }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Esping-Andersen | first1 = G\u00f8sta | last2 =Rein | first2 = Martin | last3 = Rainwater | first3 = Lee | title = Stagnation and renewal in social policy: the rise and fall of policy regimes | publisher = M.E. Sharpe | location = Armonk, New York | year = 1987 | isbn = 9780873323901 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = The three worlds of welfare capitalism | publisher = Princeton University Press | location = Princeton, New Jersey | year = 1990 | isbn = 9780069028573 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = Changing classes stratification and mobility in post-industrial societies | publisher = Sage Publications | location = London Newbury Park, California | year = 1993 | isbn = 9781849208253 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = Welfare states in transition national adaptations in global economies | publisher = Sage | location = London Thousand Oaks, California | year = 1996 | isbn = 9780857021861 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = Social foundations of postindustrial economies | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford New York | year = 1999 | isbn = 9780198742005 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Esping-Andersen | first1 = G\u00f8sta | last2 = Regini | first2 = Marino | title = Why deregulate labour markets | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford UK New York | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780199240524 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Esping-Andersen | first1 = G\u00f8sta | last2 = Gallie | first2 = Duncan | last3 = Hemerijck | first3 = Anton | last4 = Myles | first4 = John | title = Why we need a new welfare state | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = New York | year = 2002 | isbn = 9780199256433 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = Family formation and family dilemmas in contemporary Europe | publisher = Fundaci\u00f3n BBVA | location = Bilbao Spain | year = 2007 | isbn = 9788496515352 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = The incomplete revolution: adapting to women's new roles | publisher = Polity | location = Cambridge, UK Malden, Massachusetts | year = 2009 | isbn = 9780745643168 }} \nEsping-Andersen, Gosta  Families in the 21st Century (Stockholm, 2016).\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Subject bar|portal1=Biography|portal2=Society|portal3=Politics|portal4=Economics|portal5=Denmark}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Esping-Andersen, Gosta}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Danish academics]]\n[[Category:Danish political scientists]]\n[[Category:Danish sociologists]]\n[[Category:European University Institute faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pompeu Fabra University faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = G\u00f8sta Esping-Andersen\n| image       =\n| image_size  =\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1947|11|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[N\u00e6stved]], [[Denmark]]\n|field = [[Sociology]], [[Social Policy|Comparative Social Policy]]\n|work_institutions = [[Harvard University]]<br />[[European University Institute]]<br />[[Pompeu Fabra University]]\n|alma_mater = [[University of Copenhagen]]<br />[[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]\n|thesis_title = Social Class, Social Democracy and State Policy: Parity Policy and Party Decomposition in Denmark and Sweden<ref>{{cite book |last=Esping-Andersen |first=G\u00f8sta |date=1978 |title=Social Class, Social Democracy and State Policy: Parity Policy and Party Decomposition in Denmark and Sweden |type=Ph.D. |chapter= |publisher=University of Wisconsin-Madison |docket= |oclc= 705977095 |id={{ProQuest|302910232}} }}</ref>\n|known_for = ''Welfare Regimes''{{*}}''Three Worlds of Welfare Capitalism''\n}}\n\n'''G\u00f8sta Esping-Andersen''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8j\u00f8st\u00e6 \u02c8\u025bspe\u014b \u02c8an\u0250sn\u0329|pron}}) (born 24 November 1947)<ref name=Congress>{{cite web |title= Esping-Andersen, G\u00f8sta, 1947\u2013 |url= http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n84135803.html |publisher= Library of Congress |accessdate= 4 January 2015 |quote= pub. info sheet (b. 11/24/47, Naestved, Denmark; Ph.D., 1978, Univ. of Wisconsin-Madison, sociology; Dept. of Sociology, Harvard Univ., assoc. prof., Cambrdige, Mass.) }}</ref> is a Danish [[sociologist]] whose primary focus has been on the [[welfare state]] and its place in [[capitalism|capitalist economies]]. [[Jacob Hacker]] describes him as the \"dean of welfare state scholars.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hacker|first=Jacob|title=Beyond continuity:institutional change in advanced political economies|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2005|isbn=|location=|pages=|chapter=Policy Drift: The Hidden Politics of US Welfare State Retrenchment}}</ref> Over the past decade his research has moved towards family demographic issues. A synthesis of his work was published as ''Families in the 21st Century'' (Stockholm, SNS, 2016). \n\nEsping-Andersen is [[professor emeritus]] at [[Pompeu Fabra University]] in [[Barcelona]] ([[Spain]]), and member of the Scientific Committee of the [[Juan March Institute]] and of the Board of Trustees and the Scientific Council at the [[IMDEA]] Social Sciences Institute, both in [[Madrid]] ([[Spain]]). He is a member of the American Academy of Social Sciences and the British Academy. He was awarded a honoris doctor causa from Copenhagen University in 2012. He is now research professor at Bocconi University in Milano.\n\n==Major works==\nHis major, most influential and highly cited book titled ''[[The Three Worlds of Welfare Capitalism]]''<ref>{{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = The three worlds of welfare capitalism | publisher = Princeton University Press | location = Princeton, New Jersey | year = 1990 | isbn = 9780069028573 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta |  ref = harv | doi = 10.1080/15579336.1990.11770001 | title = 4 the Three Political Economies of the Welfare State | journal = International Journal of Sociology | volume = 20 | issue = 3 | pages = 92\u2013123 | year = 1990 }}</ref> was published in 1990 and it laid out three main types of [[welfare state]]s, in which modern developed capitalist nations cluster: \n*Liberal\n*Corporatist-Statist\n*Social Democratic\n\nIt is important to note that these categories have little to do with the contemporary labels of [[American politics]], and rather have much more to do with general [[political theory]]. The traditional examples of the three types of welfare states are the [[United States]] (liberal), [[Germany]] (corporatist-statist) and [[Sweden]] (social democratic).\n\nOther sociologists and political scientists went on to apply his theoretical analysis to the real world. One such example is a book entitled ''[[Real Worlds of Welfare Capitalism]]'', written by [[Robert E. Goodin]], Bruce Headey, Ruud Muffels, and Henk-Jan Dirven.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Goodin | first1 = Robert E. | last2 = Headey | first2 = Bruce | last3 = Muffels | first3 = Rudd | last4 = Dirven | first4 = Henk-Jan | author-link1 = Robert E. Goodin | title = The real worlds of welfare capitalism | url = https://archive.org/details/realworldsofwelf00robe | url-access = registration | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge, U.K. New York | year = 1999 | isbn = 9780521596398 }}</ref> While some critics claim Esping-Andersen's categories are becoming outdated, many political scientists are attracted by its intuitive simplicity.\n\nIn the past decade, his research has moved to demographic issues and in particular to the consequences of women's changing roles. He has, most notably, developed a multiple equilibrium framework for the understanding of changing family behavior. See in particular his ''''Families in the 21st Century and Esping-Andersen and Billari (2015) 'Retheorizing family demographic change'. ''Population and Development Review (2015)''''''''\n\n==Criticism==\n\nThe evolving nature of welfare states often makes it difficult to categorize. Arguably, many welfare states have components from some or all typologies, making them more akin to points on a continuum rather than rigid typologies, a fact Esping-Andersen acknowledges in his writings.\n\nAccording to French sociologist, [[Georges Menahem]], Esping-Andersen's \"[[decommodification]] index\" aggregates both qualitative and quantitative variables for \u201dsets of dimensions\u201d which fluid, and pertain to three very different areas.  Similarly, Menahem has concerns regarding the validity of the index, and its potential for replication.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Menahem | first = Georges | author-link = Helena Flam | title = The decommodified security ratio: A tool for assessing European social protection systems | journal = [[International Social Security Review]] | volume = 60 | issue = 4 | pages = 69\u2013103 | doi = 10.1111/j.1468-246X.2007.00281.x | date = October 2007 | ref = harv | url = https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00198398/file/ISSR-2007-4-TheDSRatoolforassessing.pdf }}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n=== Books ===\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = Social class, social democracy and state policy: party policy and party decomposition in Denmark and Sweden | publisher = Institute of Organization and Industrial Sociology | location = Copenhagen | year = 1980 | isbn = 9788770341790 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Esping-Andersen | first1 = G\u00f8sta | last2 = Zeitlin | first2 = Maurice | last3 = Friedland | first3 = Roger | title = Political power and social theory: a research annual, volume 3 | publisher = Jai Press Inc. | location = Greenwich, Connecticut | year = 1982 | isbn = 9780892322046 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = Politics against markets: the social democratic road to power | publisher = Princeton University Press | location = Princeton, New Jersey | year = 1985 | isbn = 9780691028422 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/politicsagainstm0000espi }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Esping-Andersen | first1 = G\u00f8sta | last2 =Rein | first2 = Martin | last3 = Rainwater | first3 = Lee | title = Stagnation and renewal in social policy: the rise and fall of policy regimes | publisher = M.E. Sharpe | location = Armonk, New York | year = 1987 | isbn = 9780873323901 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = The three worlds of welfare capitalism | publisher = Princeton University Press | location = Princeton, New Jersey | year = 1990 | isbn = 9780069028573 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = Changing classes stratification and mobility in post-industrial societies | publisher = Sage Publications | location = London Newbury Park, California | year = 1993 | isbn = 9781849208253 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = Welfare states in transition national adaptations in global economies | publisher = Sage | location = London Thousand Oaks, California | year = 1996 | isbn = 9780857021861 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = Social foundations of postindustrial economies | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford New York | year = 1999 | isbn = 9780198742005 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Esping-Andersen | first1 = G\u00f8sta | last2 = Regini | first2 = Marino | title = Why deregulate labour markets | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford UK New York | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780199240524 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Esping-Andersen | first1 = G\u00f8sta | last2 = Gallie | first2 = Duncan | last3 = Hemerijck | first3 = Anton | last4 = Myles | first4 = John | title = Why we need a new welfare state | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = New York | year = 2002 | isbn = 9780199256433 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = Family formation and family dilemmas in contemporary Europe | publisher = Fundaci\u00f3n BBVA | location = Bilbao Spain | year = 2007 | isbn = 9788496515352 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Esping-Andersen | first = G\u00f8sta | title = The incomplete revolution: adapting to women's new roles | publisher = Polity | location = Cambridge, UK Malden, Massachusetts | year = 2009 | isbn = 9780745643168 }} \nEsping-Andersen, Gosta  Families in the 21st Century (Stockholm, 2016).\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Subject bar|portal1=Biography|portal2=Society|portal3=Politics|portal4=Economics|portal5=Denmark}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Esping-Andersen, Gosta}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Danish academics]]\n[[Category:Danish political scientists]]\n[[Category:Danish sociologists]]\n[[Category:European University Institute faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pompeu Fabra University faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixingDanish IPA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G%C3%B8sta_Esping-Andersen"}
{"title_page": "Jesper J\u00f8rgensen", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Jesper J\u00f8rgensen (footballer, born 1983)}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Jesper J\u00f8rgensen\n| image = Jesper Jorgensen Club Brugge.jpg\n| caption =\n| fullname = Jesper J\u00f8rgensen\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1984|5|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Varde]], [[Denmark]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| height = {{convert|1.84|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = JBS\n| youthyears2 = 2002\u20132003 | youthclubs2 = [[Varde IF]]\n| years1 = 2003\u20132010 | clubs1 = [[Esbjerg fB]] | caps1 = 173 | goals1 = 9\n| years2 = 2011\u20132012 | clubs2 = [[K.A.A. Gent|Gent]] | caps2 = 60 | goals2 = 14\n| years3 = 2012\u20132014 | clubs3 = [[Club Brugge K.V.|Club Brugge]] | caps3 = 75 | goals3 = 10\n| years4 = 2014\u20132016 | clubs4 = [[S.V. Zulte Waregem|Zulte Waregem]] | caps4 = 36 | goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 2016\u20132018 | clubs5 = [[Esbjerg fB]] | caps5 = 34 | goals5 = 1\n| nationalyears1 = 2001\u20132002 | nationalteam1 = [[Denmark national under-19 football team|Denmark U19]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 4 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2003 | nationalteam2 = [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Denmark U21]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 4 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| pcupdate = 12 April 2018\n| ntupdate = 25 July 2003\n}}\n\n'''Jesper J\u00f8rgensen''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8jesp\u0250 \u02c8j\u0276\u0250\u032f\u02c0\u0250nsn\u0329}}; born 9 May 1984 in [[Varde]]) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] former [[Football (soccer)|football]]er.\n\n==Career==\nJ\u00f8rgensen began his career with Janderup Billum Samarbejde (JBS) and signed in July 2002 for local rival [[Varde IF]]. After one year J\u00f8rgensen left [[Varde IF]] and his hometown to sign with [[Esbjerg fB]] in summer 2003.<ref>[http://www.efb.dk/nc/fodbold/truppen/spillervisning.html?tx_wkleague_pi1&#91;playerID&#93;=282 Esbjerg fB profile]</ref>\n\nAfter 201 matches for [[Esbjerg fB|Esbjerg]] he announced his move to [[KAA Gent|Gent]] in the winter transfer window.<ref>{{cite web|publisher= DR|title=Esbjerg mister anf\u00f8rer til Gent|url=http://www.dr.dk/Sporten/Fodbold/Superliga/2010/12/10/182817.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, [[Club Brugge K.V.|Club Brugge]] announced that J\u00f8rgensen signed a three-year contract with the club.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eeckhaut|first1=Dimitri|title=Gentenaar J\u00f8rgensen eerste zomertransfer Club Brugge|trans-title=Ghent player J\u00f8rgensen is Club Brugge's first summer transfer|url=http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/1285/Jupiler-Pro-League/article/detail/1448399/2012/06/04/Gentenaar-J-rgensen-eerste-zomertransfer-Club-Brugge.dhtml|accessdate=5 January 2016|work=[[Het Laatste Nieuws]]|date=4 August 2012|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nThe midfielder played international for the U-19 four matches and four for the Under-20 team.<ref>[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/4831 National team profile]</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Season !! Club !!Competition \n|-\n| Youth || [[JBS (sport club)|JBS]] || [[Youthleague]] \n|-\n| 2002/2003 || [[Varde IF]] || [[Youthleague]] \n|-\n|2003/2010 || [[Esbjerg fB]] ||[[Danish Superliga]]\n|-\n|2011/2012 || [[AA Gent]] || [[Belgian Pro League|Jupiler Pro League]] \n|-\n|2012/- || [[Club Brugge K.V.|Club Brugge]] || [[Belgian Pro League|Jupiler Pro League]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070309090046/http://resol.dr.dk/sportservice_person.aspx?personid=456953 Career statistics] at [[Danmarks Radio]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jorgensen, Jesper}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Varde Municipality]]\n[[Category:Danish footballers]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Esbjerg fB players]]\n[[Category:Galway United F.C. (1937\u20132011) players]]\n[[Category:K.A.A. Gent players]]\n[[Category:Club Brugge KV players]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n\n\n{{Denmark-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Jesper J\u00f8rgensen (footballer, born 1983)}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Jesper J\u00f8rgensen\n| image = Jesper Jorgensen Club Brugge.jpg\n| caption =\n| fullname = Jesper J\u00f8rgensen\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1984|5|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Varde]], [[Denmark]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| height = {{convert|1.84|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = JBS\n| youthyears2 = 2002\u20132003 | youthclubs2 = [[Varde IF]]\n| years1 = 2003\u20132010 | clubs1 = [[Esbjerg fB]] | caps1 = 173 | goals1 = 9\n| years2 = 2011\u20132012 | clubs2 = [[K.A.A. Gent|Gent]] | caps2 = 60 | goals2 = 14\n| years3 = 2012\u20132014 | clubs3 = [[Club Brugge K.V.|Club Brugge]] | caps3 = 75 | goals3 = 10\n| years4 = 2014\u20132016 | clubs4 = [[S.V. Zulte Waregem|Zulte Waregem]] | caps4 = 36 | goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 2016\u20132018 | clubs5 = [[Esbjerg fB]] | caps5 = 34 | goals5 = 1\n| nationalyears1 = 2001\u20132002 | nationalteam1 = [[Denmark national under-19 football team|Denmark U19]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 4 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2003 | nationalteam2 = [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Denmark U21]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 4 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| pcupdate = 12 April 2018\n| ntupdate = 25 July 2003\n}}\n\n'''Jesper J\u00f8rgensen''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8j\u025bsp\u0250 \u02c8j\u0276\u0250\u032f\u02c0\u0250nsn\u0329}}; born 9 May 1984 in [[Varde]]) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] former [[Football (soccer)|football]]er.\n\n==Career==\nJ\u00f8rgensen began his career with Janderup Billum Samarbejde (JBS) and signed in July 2002 for local rival [[Varde IF]]. After one year J\u00f8rgensen left [[Varde IF]] and his hometown to sign with [[Esbjerg fB]] in summer 2003.<ref>[http://www.efb.dk/nc/fodbold/truppen/spillervisning.html?tx_wkleague_pi1&#91;playerID&#93;=282 Esbjerg fB profile]</ref>\n\nAfter 201 matches for [[Esbjerg fB|Esbjerg]] he announced his move to [[KAA Gent|Gent]] in the winter transfer window.<ref>{{cite web|publisher= DR|title=Esbjerg mister anf\u00f8rer til Gent|url=http://www.dr.dk/Sporten/Fodbold/Superliga/2010/12/10/182817.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, [[Club Brugge K.V.|Club Brugge]] announced that J\u00f8rgensen signed a three-year contract with the club.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eeckhaut|first1=Dimitri|title=Gentenaar J\u00f8rgensen eerste zomertransfer Club Brugge|trans-title=Ghent player J\u00f8rgensen is Club Brugge's first summer transfer|url=http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/1285/Jupiler-Pro-League/article/detail/1448399/2012/06/04/Gentenaar-J-rgensen-eerste-zomertransfer-Club-Brugge.dhtml|accessdate=5 January 2016|work=[[Het Laatste Nieuws]]|date=4 August 2012|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nThe midfielder played international for the U-19 four matches and four for the Under-20 team.<ref>[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/4831 National team profile]</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Season !! Club !!Competition \n|-\n| Youth || [[JBS (sport club)|JBS]] || [[Youthleague]] \n|-\n| 2002/2003 || [[Varde IF]] || [[Youthleague]] \n|-\n|2003/2010 || [[Esbjerg fB]] ||[[Danish Superliga]]\n|-\n|2011/2012 || [[AA Gent]] || [[Belgian Pro League|Jupiler Pro League]] \n|-\n|2012/- || [[Club Brugge K.V.|Club Brugge]] || [[Belgian Pro League|Jupiler Pro League]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070309090046/http://resol.dr.dk/sportservice_person.aspx?personid=456953 Career statistics] at [[Danmarks Radio]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jorgensen, Jesper}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Varde Municipality]]\n[[Category:Danish footballers]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Esbjerg fB players]]\n[[Category:Galway United F.C. (1937\u20132011) players]]\n[[Category:K.A.A. Gent players]]\n[[Category:Club Brugge KV players]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n\n\n{{Denmark-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixingDanish IPA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jesper_J%C3%B8rgensen"}
{"title_page": "Alma Swanley F.C.", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname   = Alma Swanley\n| image      = \n| fullname   = Alma Swanley Football Club\n| nickname   = The Alma\n| founded    = Early 1960s\n| dissolved  = 1994\n| ground     = Greencourt Road Swanley from 1982 having previously located at Swanley Recreation Ground.\n| capacity   = \n| chairman   = \n| mgrtitle   =\n| manager    = \n| league     = \n| season   = Final season<br /> 1993\u201394\n| position = <br />5th in [[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n| pattern_la1=|pattern_b1=|pattern_ra1=|leftarm1=|body1=|rightarm1=|shorts1=|socks1=|\n| pattern_la2=|pattern_b2=|pattern_ra2=|leftarm2=|body2=|rightarm2=|shorts2=|socks2=|\n}}\n'''Alma Swanley F.C''' was an English [[association football|football]] club based in [[Swanley]].They were originally known as Alma after the pub in Birchwood (lastly known as The Birchwood before being demolished in 2011) near the Bull Hotel. They originally played in the Dartford and District league, with ex Swanley Comprehensive School boys. They had to include \"Swanley\" within their name for senior status. They were founding members of the [[London Spartan League]] in 1975 and joined the [[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] in 1982. They won the title in 1986 but resigned from the league in 1994 and folded.<ref>{{cite web | date=2003-06-27 | url=http://www.kentishfootball.co.uk/othernews/27thjune03.html | title=THE CHANGING FACE OF THE KENT LEAGUE | publisher=kentishfootball.co.uk | last=Head | first=Colin | accessdate=2007-03-01 | quote=....sadly other local teams to me started to fold in the mid-1990s including former champions Alma Swanley & Darenth Heathside. | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723133522/http://www.kentishfootball.co.uk/othernews/27thjune03.html | archivedate=2011-07-23 }}</ref>\n\nThe club competed in the [[FA Cup]] six times, with the best performance coming in their final season in the competition, 1992\u201393, when they lost in the second qualifying round to [[Yeading F.C.|Yeading]]. In the [[FA Vase]], their longest run was to the Quarter Finals in 1980\u201381. They played [[Windsor & Eton F.C.|Windsor & Eton]] and after a 2\u20132 draw AET at home on Swanley Rec, with goals from Colin Ball and player manager Johnny Kane in front of a record 1,100 crowd they were defeated 4\u20131 in the replay.\n\nAlma ended their final season 1993\u201394 as winners of the Kent Senior Trophy. They defeated Folkestone Invicta 3\u20131 in the final. One of their goalscorers was [[Peter Smith (English footballer, born 1969)|Peter Smith]] who afterwards played first team professional football for [[Brighton & Hove Albion]].\n\nThe club colours were red & black.\n\n==League history==\n''League history is not complete''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n|-\n!Season\n!Division\n!Position\n!Significant events\n|-\n!colspan=4|Joined newly formed [[London Spartan League]] Division One'''\n|-\n|1975\u201376\n|[[London Spartan League]] Division One\n|3\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|- style=\"background: #90EE90;\"\n|1976\u201377\n|[[London Spartan League]] Division One\n|2\n|[[Promoted]]\n|-\n|1977\u201378\n|[[London Spartan League]] Premier Division\n|3\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1978\u201379\n|[[London Spartan League]] Premier Division\n|12\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1979\u201380\n|[[London Spartan League]] Premier Division\n|12\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1980\u201381\n|[[London Spartan League]] Premier Division\n|9\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1981\u201382\n|[[London Spartan League]] Premier Division\n|7\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n!colspan=4|Joined [[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One'''\n|-\n|1982\u201383\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|11\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1983\u201384\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|13\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1984\u201385\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|11\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|- style=\"background: #97DEFF;\"\n|1985\u201386\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|1\n| '''Champions'''\n|-\n|1986\u201387\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|3\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1987\u201388\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|12\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1988\u201389\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|6\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1989\u201390\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|5\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1990\u201391\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|8\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1991\u201392\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|5\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1992\u201393\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|5\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1993\u201394\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|5\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n!colspan=4|Left [[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{Fchd|name=Alma Swanley|id=ALMA-SWA}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs disestablished in 1994]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan\u2013London League]]\n[[Category:1994 disestablishments in England]]\n[[Category:Southern Counties East Football League]]\n[[Category:Swanley]]\n[[Category:Defunct football clubs in Kent]]\n\n\n{{England-footyclub-defunct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname   = Alma Swanley\n| image      = \n| fullname   = Alma Swanley Football Club\n| nickname   = The Alma\n| founded    = Early 1960s\n| dissolved  = 1994\n| ground     = Greencourt Road Swanley from 1982 having previously located at Swanley Recreation Ground.\n| capacity   = \n| chairman   = \n| mgrtitle   =\n| manager    = \n| league     = \n| season   = Final season<br /> 1993\u201394\n| position = <br />5th in [[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n| pattern_la1=|pattern_b1=|pattern_ra1=|leftarm1=|body1=|rightarm1=|shorts1=|socks1=|\n| pattern_la2=|pattern_b2=|pattern_ra2=|leftarm2=|body2=|rightarm2=|shorts2=|socks2=|\n}}\n'''Alma Swanley F.C''' was an English [[association football|football]] club based in [[Swanley]].They were originally known as Alma after the pub in Birchwood (lastly known as The Birchwood before being demolished in 2011) near the Bull Hotel. They originally played in the Dartford and District league, with ex Swanley Comprehensive School boys. They had to include \"Swanley\" within their name for senior status. They were founding members of the [[London Spartan League]] in 1975 and joined the [[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] in 1982. They won the title in 1986 but resigned from the league in 1994 and folded.<ref>{{cite web | date=2003-06-27 | url=http://www.kentishfootball.co.uk/othernews/27thjune03.html | title=THE CHANGING FACE OF THE KENT LEAGUE | publisher=kentishfootball.co.uk | last=Head | first=Colin | accessdate=2007-03-01 | quote=....sadly other local teams to me started to fold in the mid-90\u2019s including former champions Alma Swanley & Darenth Heathside. | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723133522/http://www.kentishfootball.co.uk/othernews/27thjune03.html | archivedate=2011-07-23 }}</ref>\n\nThe club competed in the [[FA Cup]] six times, with the best performance coming in their final season in the competition, 1992\u201393, when they lost in the second qualifying round to [[Yeading F.C.|Yeading]]. In the [[FA Vase]], their longest run was to the Quarter Finals in 1980\u201381. They played [[Windsor & Eton F.C.|Windsor & Eton]] and after a 2\u20132 draw AET at home on Swanley Rec, with goals from Colin Ball and player manager Johnny Kane in front of a record 1,100 crowd they were defeated 4\u20131 in the replay.\n\nAlma ended their final season 1993\u201394 as winners of the Kent Senior Trophy. They defeated Folkestone Invicta 3\u20131 in the final. One of their goalscorers was [[Peter Smith (English footballer, born 1969)|Peter Smith]] who afterwards played first team professional football for [[Brighton & Hove Albion]].\n\nThe club colours were red & black.\n\n==League history==\n''League history is not complete''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n|-\n!Season\n!Division\n!Position\n!Significant events\n|-\n!colspan=4|Joined newly formed [[London Spartan League]] Division One'''\n|-\n|1975\u201376\n|[[London Spartan League]] Division One\n|3\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|- style=\"background: #90EE90;\"\n|1976\u201377\n|[[London Spartan League]] Division One\n|2\n|[[Promoted]]\n|-\n|1977\u201378\n|[[London Spartan League]] Premier Division\n|3\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1978\u201379\n|[[London Spartan League]] Premier Division\n|12\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1979\u201380\n|[[London Spartan League]] Premier Division\n|12\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1980\u201381\n|[[London Spartan League]] Premier Division\n|9\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1981\u201382\n|[[London Spartan League]] Premier Division\n|7\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n!colspan=4|Joined [[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One'''\n|-\n|1982\u201383\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|11\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1983\u201384\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|13\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|1984\u201385\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|11\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|-\n|- style=\"background: #97DEFF;\"\n|1985\u201386\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Division One\n|1\n| '''Champions'''\n|-\n|1986\u201387\n|[[Southern Counties East Football League|Kent League]] Divi